erty)."]}]},{"name":"Broyes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Breyhel</b>, a variant of <b>Breil</b>, itself a variant of <b>Brühl</b> (see   Bruehl  ). The surname <i>Breyhel</i> is no longer found in Germany. Compare   Briles  .","History: Johannes Breyhel and his family, from Oetisheim in Württemberg, were among a group of German colonists sponsored by VA Governor Alexander Spotswood in 1714. They founded a settlement called Germanna in Orange County. Hans Jacob Breyhel (born 1705) was the ancestor of the Broyles family, while his brother Conrad was founder of the Briles family."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruehl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Armin, Dieter, Frieda, Horst, Lothar.","German (<b>Brühl</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a swampy area, Middle High German <i>brüel</i>, Middle Low German <i>brūl</i> ‘swampy land with brushwood’.","German and Jewish (western Ashkenazic) (<b>Brühl</b>): habitational name from Brühl in Germany. Compare   Bruhl  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":8,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":28,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":38,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":48,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alditha Isabel de Broyes was born in 1058, in Greystoke, Cumberland, England, her father, Sir Barthélemy de Broyes, was 30 and her mother, Lady Elizabeth de Valois, was 21. She married Forne Sigulfsson de Greystoke in 1074, in Greystoke, Cumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1112, in her hometown, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1058–1112":"1058–1112","1062–1112":"1062–1112","1048–1129":"1048–1129","1075–1152":"1075–1152","1080–1156":"1080–1156","1084–1152":"1084–1152","1028–1072":"1028–1072","1038–1101":"1038–1101","1080":"1080","from 1093 to 1101":"1093 kuni 1101","about 1080":"umbes 1080","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1152":"1152","1075":"1075","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1084":"1084","1062":"1062","1072":"1072","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","1028":"1028","1038":"1038","1048":"1048","1058":"1058","1112":"1112","1101":"1101","1156":"1156","about 1075":"umbes 1075","Gre